---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'athabasca-valles');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Athabasca Valles location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Athabasca Valles - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-orange-900 to-red-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Thermal emission data revealing the lava-draped channels of Athabasca Valles
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/JPL/ASU</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Athabasca Valles represents one of Mars' most geologically young and 
          extraordinary features - a flood-lava channel system that may have formed 
          as recently as 20 million years ago. This remarkable outflow channel, 
          stretching over 300 kilometers southeast of Elysium Mons, provides unique 
          insights into Mars' recent geological activity and potential water-lava 
          interactions.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          What makes Athabasca Valles truly exceptional is its dual nature: originally 
          carved by catastrophic water floods bursting from the Cerberus Fossae 
          fractures, the channels were later completely draped by a massive lava flow. 
          This lava unit is as large as Oregon and represents one of the largest flood 
          lava provinces ever identified on Mars.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Recent 2024 research has revealed new evidence suggesting either more massive 
          flooding events than previously thought, or climate conditions that allowed 
          equatorial ice preservation - findings that revolutionize our understanding 
          of Mars' recent geological and climate history.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Length:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">~300 km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Formation Age:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">~20 million years ago</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Origin:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Cerberus Fossae fractures</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Lava Unit Size:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">~250,000 km² (Oregon-sized)</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Key Feature:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Youngest outflow channel on Mars</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Geological Formation Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Dual Formation Process: Water Then Lava
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Athabasca Valles tells a complex geological story involving two distinct 
        catastrophic events separated by potentially millions of years. The channel 
        system records both the most recent major flood event on Mars and one of 
        its youngest volcanic eruptions.
      </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Phase 1: Catastrophic Flooding</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Water burst from Cerberus Fossae fractures</li>
            <li>• Groundwater trapped under ice layer released</li>
            <li>• Flow rates: 10,000-10 million m³/second</li>
            <li>• Carved distinctive channel morphology</li>
            <li>• Evidence of turbulent water flow patterns</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Phase 2: Lava Inundation</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Massive lava flow from same fissure system</li>
            <li>• Completely draped existing channels</li>
            <li>• Created Oregon-sized lava province</li>
            <li>• Preserved underlying flood morphology</li>
            <li>• Evidence of lava-ice interactions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Recent Discoveries Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Groundbreaking 2024 Research Findings
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/50 to-blue-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Climate vs. Flood Volume Paradox
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          New 2024 USGS research reveals that floods with previously estimated 
          volumes cannot reach the distal rootless cones or Lethe Vallis. This 
          finding suggests either Mars had a climate allowing equatorial ice 
          preservation, or flood events were orders of magnitude larger than 
          previously calculated.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          This discovery challenges our understanding of both Mars' recent climate 
          history and the scale of its most recent geological catastrophes.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-red-900/50 to-red-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-red-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Volcanic Rootless Cones Evidence
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Rootless cones scattered across the lava flow indicate water was present 
          in the shallow subsurface when volcanic activity occurred. These 
          formations provide direct evidence of lava-water interactions and suggest 
          water persisted in the region between the flood and volcanic events.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The distribution pattern of these cones helps scientists understand the 
          extent and timing of subsurface water availability.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Turbulent Lava Flow Analysis
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        High-resolution imaging has revealed that the Athabasca Valles flood lava 
        displays unique morphological evidence of turbulent flow - the only confirmed 
        instance of such behavior in Martian lava flows. This turbulent signature 
        suggests extremely high effusion rates and provides insights into the 
        volcanic processes that created this massive lava province.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        The preserved flow patterns indicate this was not a typical basaltic 
        eruption but rather a catastrophic volcanic event comparable to Earth's 
        largest flood basalt provinces.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Water-Lava Interactions Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Lava-Ice Interactions and Implications
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The interaction between lava flows and subsurface ice at Athabasca Valles 
          provides crucial insights into Mars' hydrological processes and recent 
          climate conditions. Recent studies suggest that large-scale lava-ice 
          interactions may have been responsible for both the formation of the 
          outflow channels and subsequent volcanic features.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Meltwater Confinement Model
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Alternative formation theories propose that lava-ice interactions 
              created confined meltwater systems that accumulated and catastrophically 
              released, potentially explaining the channel formation without requiring 
              deep groundwater sources.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Subsurface Ice Evidence
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              The presence of rootless cones indicates substantial subsurface ice 
              was available during lava emplacement, supporting theories of recent 
              ice preservation near Mars' equator.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Formation Timeline
        </h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Initial Flooding:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">~20 Ma ago</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Lava Emplacement:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">~2-5 Ma ago</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Total Duration:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">~15-18 Ma</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Preservation State:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Excellent</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Assessment Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-yellow-900/30 to-yellow-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-yellow-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-yellow-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">6</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            Moderate Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-yellow-300">
            Recent geological activity with water-lava interactions
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Evidence of recent subsurface water</li>
            <li>• Young, geologically active terrain</li>
            <li>• Volcanic resources and energy potential</li>
            <li>• Large, flat lava plains for construction</li>
            <li>• Potential geothermal activity</li>
            <li>• Well-preserved geological record</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Ongoing volcanic hazard potential</li>
            <li>• Limited current surface water access</li>
            <li>• Extreme flood risk from future events</li>
            <li>• Dust accumulation issues</li>
            <li>• Radiation exposure on open plains</li>
            <li>• Seismic instability from Cerberus Fossae</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Scientific Significance Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Scientific Significance
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Mars Climate Evolution
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Athabasca Valles provides the youngest and most complete record of major 
          geological activity on Mars. The evidence of recent water-lava interactions 
          challenges conventional models of Mars' transition to its current cold, 
          dry state and suggests more complex climate evolution than previously thought.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Comparative Planetology
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          As the only confirmed example of turbulent flood lava on Mars, Athabasca 
          Valles provides crucial data for understanding volcanic processes on other 
          planets. The scale and characteristics of this lava province exceed many 
          comparable features on Earth, offering insights into planetary-scale 
          volcanic processes.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Exploration Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Future Exploration Potential
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        As Mars' youngest major geological feature, Athabasca Valles represents 
        a unique opportunity to study recent planetary processes and potential 
        ongoing activity. The region's geological youth and preserved features 
        make it an ideal target for understanding Mars' transition from ancient 
        water activity to its current state.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Research Priorities
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Subsurface ice detection and mapping</li>
            <li>• Volcanic hazard assessment</li>
            <li>• Detailed chronology of water-lava events</li>
            <li>• Rootless cone formation mechanisms</li>
            <li>• Climate modeling validation</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Exploration Methods
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Ground-penetrating radar surveys</li>
            <li>• Seismic monitoring networks</li>
            <li>• Sample collection from lava flows</li>
            <li>• Thermal imaging of fracture systems</li>
            <li>• Long-term geological monitoring</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://mars.nasa.gov/resources/26922/athabasca-valles/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              NASA Mars Exploration: Athabasca Valles
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/images/pia12488-turbulent-lava-flow-in-mars-athabasca-valles/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              JPL: Turbulent Lava Flow Images
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Scientific Papers</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.usgs.gov/publications/late-amazonian-ice-near-athabasca-valles-mars-recent-megaflood-or-climate-change"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              USGS: Late Amazonian Ice Study (2024)
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.science.org/doi/abs/10.1126/science.1143315"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Science: Lava-Draped Channel System
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>